[Most likely this is in reference to _Echinococcus granulosus_. This is a
tapeworm found in the small intestine of the definitive hosts, canines and
several other wild carnivores. Its eggs are ingested by the intermediate
hosts, wild and domestic herbivores, e.g., sheep cattle, and moose and some
omnivores, e.g., pigs and man. (However, man may be both a definitive and
an intermediate host.)
After hatching in the intestine of the intermediate host, the oncospheres
(that version of the tape worm) invade the circulatory system and lodge in
various organs, usually the liver and lungs, where they develop into large,
thick-walled, hydatid cysts that bud endogenously.
Hydatids have ben rarely reported in the Central Nervous System of domestic
animals and are rare in man, in which they produce symptoms similar to
those of a brain tumor. In some cases, surgical intervention to remove the
cysts, from brain, or lungs especially, can be successful. The eggs may be
acquired from eating inadequately cooked meat that contains the cysts. -
Mod.TG]
